  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I evict a problem tenant in Queensland just because I want to sell?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. Wanting to sell is not, by itself, a ground to end a tenancy in Queensland. Under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act, you must either wait until the fixed term ends and issue a Form 12 with the minimum two months' notice, or rely on a separate ground such as unpaid rent (Form 11), serious breach (Form 11), or a tribunal order through QCAT. A genuinely problem tenant, with documented arrears or repeated breaches, is usually best handled by your property manager through the breach and remedy process before you list, not by trying to terminate purely on the basis of sale."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will a problem tenant reduce the sale price of my Brisbane investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In most cases, yes. Where a tenant is uncooperative with entry, the property presents poorly, or there are visible signs of arrears, damage, or hoarding, the buyer pool narrows sharply to investors only, photography and inspection access are restricted, and offers tend to discount 5 to 12 percent against a comparable vacant or well-tenanted equivalent. The exact discount depends on how much the tenant's behaviour limits the campaign. In Brisbane's inner east, where most stock is purchased by owner-occupiers, the loss of the owner-occupier buyer alone often costs more than the holding cost of waiting for vacant possession."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I wait for vacant possession or sell with the problem tenant in place?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If the fixed term has less than six months to run and the tenant is uncooperative, waiting for vacant possession is usually the better financial decision in Brisbane's inner east. Two to four months of additional holding cost is typically smaller than the discount an uncooperative tenanted sale attracts, and the buyer pool widens to include owner-occupiers. If the lease has more than nine months to run, the maths shifts toward selling tenanted to an investor buyer at a discount rather than carrying the property through the entire residual term. The decision should be made with a specific cost comparison from your agent and a realistic read on the tenant's likely conduct during the campaign."
      }
    }
  ]
};
